{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2b45f7a2-c495-4c8d-9718-1c3fecbf0dec","content":"Here's how to connect the MCP Inspector to your C# stdio MCP server:\n\n**1. Run the Inspector**\n```bash\nnpx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector\n```\nThis opens a web UI (usually at `http://localhost:6274`).\n\n**2. Configure the connection**\n- **Transport Type:** `STDIO`\n- **Command:** `dotnet`\n- **Arguments:** `run --project /path/to/YourServer.csproj`\n\n  *(Or if you have a built DLL: command `dotnet`, args `/path/to/YourServer.dll`)*\n\n**3. Click \"Connect\"**\n\n**4. Debug from the UI**\n- **Tools tab** — lists discovered tools; click one to invoke it with test inputs.\n- **Resources / Prompts tabs** — test those capabilities if exposed.\n- Use the **Console/Logs** pane at the bottom to see raw JSON-RPC messages exchanged over stdio.\n\n**Tips:**\n- Make sure your server writes MCP JSON-RPC to **stdout** and logs/diagnostics to **stderr** — any stray `Console.WriteLine` on stdout will break the protocol.\n- If you need environment variables, add them in the Inspector's **Environment Variables** section before connecting.\n- Add `--no-build` to the arguments if you've already built and want faster startup.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"dfc7208c-4d1c-42e0-880a-f004ce8cbd62","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to use the MCP Inspector to interactively test and debug a C# MCP server that uses stdio transport. This is a knowledge/guidance question, not a code change task. Let me provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":386,"requestId":"D024:12CCF0:18AA609:1B27EB7:6A0673B5"},"id":"95f775b0-633c-4f35-b2c2-24fdedea54d3","timestamp":"2026-05-15T01:15:43.725Z","parentId":"81a06570-dfac-4fab-8d10-e3db96cf7349"}
